<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>

<activity xml:id="act-compararDosAlgoritmosDeResta" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"> 

<title>Comparemos dos algoritmos de resta</title>

<statement>
  <ol>
    <li><p>Estos son los primeros pasos de los dos algoritmos.</p>
      <sbsgroup widths="50% 50%">
        <sidebyside>
          <p>Paso 1 del algoritmo A</p>
          <p>Paso 1 del algoritmo B</p>
        </sidebyside>
        <sidebyside>
          <image source="svg-source/tikz-file-148979">
            <shortdescription>Descomposición por valor posicional de 508</shortdescription>
          </image>
          <image source="svg-source/tikz-file-148980">
            <shortdescription>resta de las unidades</shortdescription>
          </image>
        </sidebyside>
      </sbsgroup>
      <p>
        ¿En qué son diferentes los pasos?
      </p>
    </li>
    <li><p>Usa cada algoritmo para encontrar el valor de <m>824-541</m>.</p></li>
  </ol>
</statement>

<solution>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ol>
      <li>In the first algorithm, the first step is decomposing one of the hundreds into 10 tens. In the second algorithm, the first step is subtracting the ones. Each algorithm will look the same at the end.</li>
      <li>283</li>
    </ol>
  </solution>


<!-- ============================================================== 
   Notas profesor <prelude> (se pueden mostrar previo al enunciado)                      
===================================================================  -->
<prelude component="profesor"> 

  <!-- Estándares CCSS asociados -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="ccss-actividad-titulo"/></title> 
    <ul>
      <li> 
        <custom ref="ccss-addressing"/>
        <xref ref="ccss-3-NBT-A-2" text="custom">3.NBT.A.2</xref>
      </li>  
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Tiempo recomendado -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="recommended-time-titulo"/></title>
    <p>20 minutos</p>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Introducción de la actividad -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="narrative-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p>The purpose of this activity is for students to consider two subtraction algorithms. In the first algorithm, students first look for any place value units where they need to decompose to get more units, then subtract right to left. In the second algorithm, subtraction occurs right to left, and units are decomposed as the need arises. Students try each algorithm and consider potential advantages and disadvantages of each algorithm.</p>
    <p>In the synthesis, students carefully analyze and discuss the two algorithms, explaining the motivation behind them and how they are the same and different (MP3, MP6).</p>
  </paragraphs>

  <!-- Launch -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="launch-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Groups of 2</li>
      <li>Display the image.</li>
      <li>
        <q>Estos son los primeros pasos de dos algoritmos de resta. Tómense un minuto para pensar en qué son diferentes</q>
      </li>
      <li>1 minute: quiet think time</li>
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>


  <!-- Instrucciones para el desarrollo de la actividad -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="instructions-teacher-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <q>Con su pareja, discutan las diferencias en los pasos de cada algoritmo</q>
      </li>
      <li>2 minutes: partner discussion</li>
      <li>Share and record responses.</li>
      <li>
        <q>Con su pareja, terminen cada algoritmo</q>
      </li>
      <li>2–3 minutes: partner work time</li>
      <li>
        <q>Ahora, con su pareja, usen los dos algoritmos para restarle 541 a 824</q>
      </li>
      <li>5–7 minutes: partner work time</li>
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>

</prelude>


<!-- ============================================================== 
   Notas profesor <postlude> (se pueden mostrar después del enunciado)                      
===================================================================  -->
<postlude component="profesor">

  <!-- Síntesis de la actividad -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="synthesis-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[+++++++++++++++]</p>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Select students to share how they used both algorithms to find the value of <m>824 - 541</m>.</p></li>
      <li>Keep algorithms from the first problem displayed.</li>
      <li>
        <q>Aunque puede que los algoritmos parezcan ser el mismo después de unos pasos, estos empezaron de manera diferente. Piensen sobre las ventajas y desventajas de usar cada algoritmo</q>
      </li>
      <li>1 minute: quiet think time</li>
      <li>
        <q>Ahora discutan con su pareja sobre las ventajas y desventajas de cada algoritmo</q>
      </li>
      <li>1 minute: partner discussion</li>
      <li>Invite students to share advantages and disadvantages they come up with. (In algorithm 1, I look for decompositions first, so I probably won’t mix up the order of subtracting. In algorithm 1, I could subtract left to right or right to left. In algorithm 2, I can start subtracting right away. That means I don’t have to worry about decomposing until I know I need to do it.)</li>
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>


  <!-- Descripción del desarrollo de lenguaje matemático -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="language-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[++++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p><em>MLR8 Discussion Supports.</em></p>
    <p>Synthesis: For each idea that is shared, invite students to turn to a partner and restate what they heard using precise mathematical language.</p>
  </paragraphs>


  <!-- Estrategias de acceso para estudiantes con discapacidades -->
  <paragraphs>
    <title><custom ref="accesibility-actividad-titulo"/></title>
    <p>[++++++++++++++++]</p>
    <p><em>Engagement: Develop Effort and Persistence.</em> Some students may benefit from feedback that emphasizes effort, and time on task. For example, check in with students after completing the problem using the first algorithm.</p>
    <p>
      <em>Supports accessibility for: Attention</em>
    </p>
  </paragraphs>

</postlude>

</activity>